The following problem is shown to be decidable. Given are homomorphisms h<subscrpt>1</subscrpt> and h<subscrpt>2</subscrpt> from &Sgr;* to &Sgr;* and strings &sgr;<subscrpt>1</subscrpt> and &sgr;<subscrpt>2</subscrpt> over &Sgr; such that h<supscrpt>n</supscrpt><subscrpt>i</subscrpt>(&sgr;<subscrpt>i</subscrpt>) is a proper prefix of h<supscrpt>n+1</supscrpt><subscrpt>i</subscrpt> (&sgr;<subscrpt>i</subscrpt>) for i &equil; 1, 2 and all n ≥ 0, i.e. for i &equil; 1, 2, h<subscrpt>i</subscrpt> generates from &sgr;<subscrpt>i</subscrpt> an infinite string α<subscrpt>i</subscrpt> with prefixes h<supscrpt>n</supscrpt><subscrpt>i</subscrpt>(&sgr;<subscrpt>i</subscrpt>) for all n ≥ 0. Test whether α<subscrpt>1</subscrpt> &equil; α<subscrpt>2</subscrpt>. From this result easily follows the decidability of limit language equivalence (ω-equivalence) for DOL systems.